---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { siteMeta } from "@/lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout title="Install" description="Install Kern from the official release archives, verify the toolchain, and understand the current host baselines.">
  <section class="manual-page mx-auto px-5 pb-20 pt-14 md:px-8 md:pt-18">
    <div class="eyebrow">Install</div>
    <h1 class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-5xl leading-[0.95] text-[color:var(--kern-ink)] md:text-6xl">
      Install Kern
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[color:rgba(21,26,32,0.76)]">
      The normal path is the official release archive plus the native installer script.
      That installs `kernc`, `craft`, `kern-lsp`, the shipped library layers, and the
      packaged host-tool payload in one predictable layout.
    </p>

    <div class="manual-callout mt-10">
      <div class="manual-kicker">Install Summary</div>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-base">
        <li>Use the release installer unless you are actively developing the compiler itself.</li>
        <li>Kern installs into `~/.kern` on Unix and `%USERPROFILE%\\.kern` on Windows.</li>
        <li>After install, verify `kernc`, `craft`, and `kern-lsp` before doing anything else.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <div class="manual-kicker">Current Official Host Baselines</div>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-base">
        <li>Linux: `x86_64-linux-gnu`, built on `ubuntu-24.04`.</li>
        <li>Windows: `x86_64-windows-msvc`, built on `windows-latest` with static CRT.</li>
        <li>macOS Intel: `x86_64-apple-darwin`, built on `macos-15-intel`.</li>
        <li>macOS Apple Silicon: `aarch64-apple-darwin`, built on `macos-14`.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        These are explicit release build baselines, not a blanket promise that one archive
        runs on every older distro, every older macOS release, or every older Windows machine.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Install Commands</h2>
      <div class="manual-grid manual-grid-2 mt-6">
        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">Linux And macOS</div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base">
            The Unix installer downloads the matching release archive and installs it into your local Kern root.
          </p>
          <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`curl -sSf https://raw.githubusercontent.com/softfault/kern/main/install.sh | bash`}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">Windows PowerShell</div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base">
            The Windows installer downloads the official SDK archive and expands the bundled host toolchain along with the Kern tools.
          </p>
          <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`powershell -Command "Set-ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Scope Process -Force; Invoke-Expression (Invoke-WebRequest -Uri https://raw.githubusercontent.com/softfault/kern/main/install.ps1 -UseBasicParsing).Content"`}</code></pre>
        </section>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Offline and repeated installs</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        Both installers support a local archive path. Use this when you want one download for repeated setups,
        when the machine is offline, or when you are validating a specific release archive by hand.
      </p>

      <div class="manual-grid mt-6">
        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">Unix local archive</div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base">
            Download `install.sh` plus the matching `.tar.gz` from GitHub Releases, then point the installer at the local archive.
          </p>
          <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`curl -fsSLO https://raw.githubusercontent.com/softfault/kern/main/install.sh
bash install.sh --archive ./kern-v0.7.0-x86_64-linux-gnu.tar.gz`}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section>
          <div class="manual-kicker">Windows local archive</div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base">
            Download `install.ps1` and the matching release zip once, then rerun it against that local file whenever needed.
          </p>
          <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\\install.ps1 -Archive .\\kern-v0.7.0-x86_64-windows-msvc.zip`}</code></pre>
          <p class="mt-4 text-base">
            If you renamed the zip, pass the version explicitly as well:
          </p>
          <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\\install.ps1 -Version v0.7.0 -Archive .\\kern.zip`}</code></pre>
        </section>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Verify the install</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        Before opening the guide, confirm that the three user-facing tools actually start.
      </p>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`kernc --version
craft --version
kern-lsp --version`}</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        If your shell still cannot find them, restart the terminal or apply the PATH change the installer printed.
      </p>

      <div class="manual-callout mt-6">
        <div class="manual-kicker">Common Failure Modes</div>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-base">
          <li>Unix startup can fail if required shared libraries such as `libstdc++`, `zlib`, or `zstd` are missing.</li>
          <li>Unix startup can also fail if the machine is older than the release archive's libc baseline.</li>
          <li>Windows first-time install can feel slow because the bundled host-tool payload is large and Defender may scan it.</li>
          <li>A successful extraction is not enough. The installed binaries still need to start on the actual host.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Related distribution docs</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        The install page covers the normal user path. More detailed release and distribution policy still lives in the repository docs for now.
      </p>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
          <a class="button-primary" href="/guide/getting-started/">
            Continue to Getting Started
          </a>
          <a class="button-secondary" href="/sdk">
            SDK layout and artifacts
          </a>
          <a class="button-secondary" href="/build-from-source">
            Build from source
          </a>
          <a class="button-secondary" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/windows-distribution.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
            Windows distribution doc
          </a>
          <a class="button-secondary" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/unix-distribution.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
            Unix distribution doc
          </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
